    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology & Montreal Definition of GERD", content: "Gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) is defined by the Montreal Consensus as a condition that develops when reflux of gastric contents causes troublesome symptoms and/or mucosal complications. The pathophysiology centers on failure of the antireflux barrier at the gastroesophageal junction (GEJ), which normally comprises the lower esophageal sphincter (LES), the crural diaphragm, and the angle of His. Transient lower esophageal sphincter relaxations (TLESRs) are the dominant mechanism in most GERD patients, accounting for approximately 70% of reflux episodes. These are vagally mediated relaxations that are not triggered by swallowing and allow gastric acid, pepsin, and bile salts to contact the esophageal squamous epithelium. The esophageal mucosa lacks the protective bicarbonate-mucus layer present in the stomach, making it vulnerable to acid-peptic injury. Prolonged acid exposure (esophageal pH < 4) causes cellular damage through hydrogen ion back-diffusion, leading to intercellular space dilation, basal cell hyperplasia, and eventually erosive esophagitis. Diagnostic evaluation relies on clinical symptom assessment (heartburn and regurgitation as cardinal symptoms), empiric PPI trial (positive response supports diagnosis), upper endoscopy (EGD) to identify erosive esophagitis graded by Los Angeles classification (grades A through D), and ambulatory reflux monitoring for patients with non-erosive reflux disease or refractory symptoms. The 24-hour pH-impedance study is the gold standard for quantifying acid and non-acid reflux, measuring total acid exposure time (AET > 6% is abnormal, < 4% is normal, 4-6% is inconclusive) and symptom-reflux correlation using symptom index (SI > 50%) and symptom association probability (SAP > 95%). The Bravo wireless pH capsule provides 48-96 hours of catheter-free pH monitoring, improving patient tolerance and diagnostic yield by capturing day-to-day variability." },
