    cellular: { title: "GERD Management and PPI Stewardship", content: "GERD management follows a stepwise approach guided by symptom severity, endoscopic findings, and objective reflux testing. The step-up strategy begins with lifestyle modifications and over-the-counter antacids or H2RAs, escalating to standard-dose PPI therapy if symptoms persist, and then to twice-daily PPI or adjunctive therapy for refractory cases. The step-down approach begins with standard-dose PPI for 8 weeks to achieve symptom control and mucosal healing, then steps down to the lowest effective dose, on-demand therapy, or H2RA maintenance. PPI stewardship is critical because these agents are among the most overprescribed medications globally, with an estimated 25-70% of PPI prescriptions lacking a clear ongoing indication. Long-term PPI risks include Clostridioides difficile infection (disrupted gastric acid barrier allows spore germination), community-acquired pneumonia, hypomagnesemia (impaired intestinal TRPM6 channel absorption), vitamin B12 deficiency (acid required for B12 liberation from food proteins), calcium malabsorption with increased fracture risk (hip, wrist, spine), fundic gland polyps (benign but concerning to patients), and acute and chronic kidney disease (acute interstitial nephritis mechanism). PPI deprescribing should be attempted in patients without strong indications for ongoing therapy. Strong indications for continued PPI include Los Angeles grade C/D esophagitis, Barrett esophagus, history of bleeding peptic ulcer with ongoing NSAID or anticoagulant use, and Zollinger-Ellison syndrome. Deprescribing strategies include dose reduction (e.g., omeprazole 40 mg to 20 mg), frequency reduction (daily to every other day), switch to H2RA, and abrupt discontinuation with on-demand use. Rebound acid hypersecretion may occur 2-4 weeks after PPI cessation due to enterochromaffin-like cell hyperplasia and hypergastrinemia, causing temporary symptom recurrence that can be managed with antacids or H2RAs." },
